Welcome back to Wall Power, where we=E2=80=99re diving into Americana
week here in New York. I=E2=80=99m Marion Maneker.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

American art may no longer get the kind of attention it used to, but that d=
oesn=E2=80=99t mean the quality has declined. Indeed, as the market=E2=80=
=99s shifted away from =E2=80=9Cbrown furniture,=E2=80=9D silver, and folk =
art toward art by overlooked creators and outsider art, the offerings have =
only become more interesting. This January, we=E2=80=99re seeing some of th=
e final
installments of financier William Louis-Dreyfus=E2=80=99s outsider art coll=
ection, as well as some dealer stock from Just Folk, the gallery co-owned b=
y sitcom producer Marcy Carsey. Tonight, I have a roundup of some of the fa=
scinating works on offer this week, from a Thomas Cole painting to Paul Rev=
ere silver. And Julie Davich tells the story of dueling Declarations of Ind=
ependence, one of which isn=E2=80=99t quite what the
clever marketing is making it seem.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But first=E2=80=A6

* New year, new Sotheby=E2=80=99s: Head of global business development Mari=
-Claudia Jim=C3=A9nez is leaving, per an internal announcement today. She l=
