0617da42abd12a )=E2=80=9D in a single-lot auction=E2=80=94a sale strategy r=
eserved for the rarest and most valuable objects that specialists are confi=
dent will spark a bidding war. Both documents have the same estimate ($2 mi=
llion), but they couldn=E2=80=99t be more different.

By way of background, the auction market for foundational American document=
s (as in, documents related to the nation=E2=80=99s founding) has exploded =
since November 2021, when Sotheby=E2=80=99s sold a historic first printing =
of the U.S. Constitution for $43.2 million. Sotheby=E2=80=99s had offered t=
he document in a single-lot auction before its contemporary art evening sal=
e=E2=80=94a strategy that opened up the sale to a much broader audience tha=
n it would otherwise have attracted.
That night, hedge fund manager Ken Griffin won the bidding after an eight-m=
inute battle, beating out a cohort of 17,000 cryptocurrency enthusiasts cal=
ling themselves ConstitutionDAO.

Then, in another headline-grabbing sale this past October, Brunk Auctions i=
n Asheville, North Carolina, sold an original printed, signed archetype of =
the Constitution for more than $11 million to an anonymous buyer.
=E2=80=9CThere is enormous interest in this field,=E2=80=9D independent app=
raiser and advisor ( https://www.leckyartgroup.com?utm_campaign=3DWall+Powe=
r+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F21%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2=
81%2F21%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=
=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) Tom Lecky told me. =E2=80=9CDealers and auction hou=
ses are chasing it.=E2=80=9D As a 17-year veteran of Christie=E2=80=99s, he=
 would know.

As for the Declarations of Independence on offer this week: Christie=E2=80=
=99s version is named for Samuel Jones, New York=E2=80=99s first comptrolle=
r, who transcribed the document. (His name might be familiar to locals as t=
he namesake of Great Jones Street. Cornelia Street is named for his wife.) =
In the lot notes, Christie=E2=80=99s describes him as an =E2=80=9Cunsung he=
ro of the early Republic,=E2=80=9D for helping to broker a compromise that =
paved the way for New York=E2=80=99s 1788
ratification of the Constitution.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But what Christie=E2=80=99s is actually selling is a handwritten copy of Ne=
w York=E2=80=99s 1777 Constitution, a 39-page document that happens to incl=
ude the full text of the Declaration of Independence. Jones likely transcri=
bed it for the state=E2=80=99s ratification convention, in 1788, to be refe=
renced or read aloud. So while it=E2=80=99s notable as the earliest known c=
omplete
manuscript of New York=E2=80=99s first constitution, I would not call it a =
=E2=80=9CDeclaration of Independence,=E2=80=9D per se. Yet, given the deman=
d for foundational American documents, it=E2=80=99s understandable=E2=80=94=
and even brilliant=E2=80=94that Christie=E2=80=99s is attempting such a mar=
keting coup. I don=E2=80=99t know what price a document promoted as =E2=80=
=9CThe Earliest Known Complete Manuscript of New York=E2=80=99s 1777 Consti=
tution, Including the Declaration of Independence, from the State=E2=80=99s=
 1788 Ratification Convention=E2=80=9D would command=E2=80=A6 but probably
not $2 million.

Meanwhile, the document on offer at Sotheby=E2=80=99s is a rare printing of=
 the Declaration of Independence from July 1776, the same month independenc=
e was declared. It last sold at Christie=E2=80=99s in April 2021 for $930,0=
00, so its $2 million estimate demonstrates the impact that $43.2 million C=
onstitution had on the market. The Exeter Broadside was printed by Robert L=
uist Fowle of Exeter, New Hampshire, and it=E2=80=99s one of only 10
remaining copies=E2=80=94most of which are in institutional collections=E2=
=80=94and one of only two to appear at auction in the past century. =E2=80=
=9CIt=E2=80=99s incredibly real and immediate when you think of these indiv=
iduals in 1776 working furiously to reproduce these documents,=E2=80=9D sai=
d Dr. Kalika Sands, Sotheby=E2=80=99s head of books and manuscripts, Americ=
