c1e1290049e29df36e8443ab62cc" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40=
000;">The Declaration of Independence: The July 1776 Exeter Broadside</a>=
=E2=80=9D in a single-lot auction=E2=80=94a sale strategy reserved for the =
rarest and most valuable objects that specialists are confident will spark =
a bidding war. Both documents have the same estimate ($2 million), but they=
 couldn=E2=80=99t be more different.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">By way of background, the auction market for foundational A=
merican documents (as in, documents related to the nation=E2=80=99s foundin=
g) has <em>exploded</em> since November 2021, when Sotheby=E2=80=99s sold a=
 historic first printing of the U.S. Constitution for $43.2 million. Sotheb=
y=E2=80=99s had offered the document in a single-lot auction before its con=
temporary art evening sale=E2=80=94a strategy that opened up the sale to a =
much broader audience than it would otherwise have attracted.
That night, hedge fund manager <strong>Ken Griffin</strong> won the bidding=
 after an eight-minute battle, beating out a cohort of 17,000 cryptocurrenc=
y enthusiasts calling themselves ConstitutionDAO.<br/><br/>Then, in another=
 headline-grabbing sale this past October, Brunk Auctions in Asheville, Nor=
th Carolina, sold an original printed, signed archetype of the Constitution=
 for more than $11 million to an anonymous buyer.
=E2=80=9CThere is enormous interest in this field,=E2=80=9D independent app=
raiser and <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z=
1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVaTZXOE1FSnZQLUIxWWRuamhrMD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
bGVja3lhcnRncm91cC5jb20_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVdhbGwrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUys=
lMjgxJTJGMjElMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVdhbGwrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQk=
VSUyslMjgxJTJGMjElMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2d=
XRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIs=
ImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MjA1MDM4MX0/ca9fb2c=
ca0df547b5e8fa7c276f6a4254fced705eac1ec19be3ffdb74a7b8424" style=3D"text-de=
coration:underline;color:#d40000;">advisor</a><span style=3D"word-break:bre=
ak-word;background-color:transparent;"></span> <strong style=3D"background-=
color:transparent;">Tom Lecky</strong><span style=3D"word-break:break-word;=
background-color:transparent;"> told me. =E2=80=9CDealers and auction house=
s are chasing it.=E2=80=9D As a 17-year veteran of Christie=E2=80=99s, he w=
ould know.</span></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><br/>As for t=
he Declarations of Independence on offer this week: Christie=E2=80=99s vers=
ion is named for <strong>Samuel Jones</strong>, New York=E2=80=99s first co=
mptroller, who transcribed the document. (His name might be familiar to loc=
als as the namesake of Great Jones Street. Cornelia Street is named for his=
 wife.) In the lot notes, Christie=E2=80=99s describes him as an =E2=80=9Cu=
nsung hero of the early Republic,=E2=80=9D for helping to broker a compromi=
se that paved the way for New York=E2=80=99s 1788
ratification of the Constitution.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But what Christ=
ie=E2=80=99s is <em>actually</em> selling is a handwritten copy of New York=
=E2=80=99s 1777 Constitution, a 39-page document that happens to include th=
e full text of the Declaration of Independence. Jones likely transcribed it=
 for the state=E2=80=99s ratification convention, in 1788, to be referenced=
 or read aloud. So while it=E2=80=99s notable as the earliest known complet=
e
manuscript of New York=E2=80=99s first constitution, I would not call it a =
=E2=80=9CDeclaration of Independence,=E2=80=9D per se. Yet, given the deman=
d for foundational American documents, it=E2=80=99s understandable=E2=80=94=
and even brilliant=E2=80=94that Christie=E2=80=99s is attempting such a mar=
keting coup. I don=E2=80=99t know what price a document promoted as =E2=80=
=9CThe Earliest Known Complete Manuscript of New York=E2=80=99s 1777 Consti=
tution, Including the Declaration of Independence, from the State=E2=80=99s=
 1788 Ratification Convention=E2=80=9D would command=E2=80=A6 but probably
<em>not</em> $2 million.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Meanwhile, the=
 document on offer at Sotheby=E2=80=99s is a rare printing of the Declarati=
on of Independence from July 1776, the same month independence was declared=
=2E It last sold at Christie=E2=80=99s in=20=
April 2021 for $930,000, so its $2=20=
million estimate demonstrates the impact that $43.2 million Constitution ha=
d on the market. The Exeter Broadside was printed by <strong>Robert Luist F=
owle </strong>of Exeter, New Hampshire, and it=E2=80=99s one of only 10
remaining copies=E2=80=94most of which are in institutional collections=E2=
=80=94and one of only two to appear at auction in the past century. =E2=80=
=9CIt=E2=80=99s incredibly real and immediate when you think of these indiv=
iduals in 1776 working furiously to reproduce these documents,=E2=80=9D sai=
d Dr. <strong>Kalika Sands</strong>, Sotheby=E2=80=99s head of books and ma=
nuscripts, Americas, =E2=80=9Cso people would know they are now part of the=
 United States of America.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
